# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: inductor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:inductor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] An **accumulator** is an energy storage device: a device which accepts energy, stores energy, and releases energy as needed.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Some accumulators accept energy at a low rate (low power) over a long time interval and deliver the energy at a high rate (high power) over a short time interval.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Some accumulators accept energy at a high rate over a short time interval and deliver the energy at a low rate over a longer time interval.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Some accumulators typically accept and release energy at comparable rates.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Various devices can store thermal energy, mechanical energy, and electrical energy.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Energy is usually accepted and delivered in the same form.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Some devices store a different form of energy than what they receive and deliver performing energy conversion on the way in and on the way out.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] Examples of accumulators include steam accumulators, mainsprings, flywheel energy storage, hydraulic accumulators, rechargeable batteries, capacitors, inductors, compensated pulsed alternators (compulsators), and pumped-storage hydroelectric plants.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] In general usage in an electrical context, the word *accumulator* normally refers to a lead–acid battery.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] The London Tower Bridge is operated via an accumulator.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] The original raising mechanism was powered by pressurised water stored in several hydraulic accumulators.
[src:inductor/accumulator-energy] In 1974, the original operating mechanism was largely replaced by a new electro-hydraulic drive system.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] An **acorn tube**, or **acorn valve**, is any member of a family of VHF/UHF vacuum tubes starting just before World War II.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] They were named after their resemblance to the acorn, specifically due to the glass cap at one end of the tube that looked similar to the cap on an acorn.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] The acorn tubes found widespread use in radios and radar systems.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] High-frequency performance is limited by (1) parasitic lead inductance and capacitance and skin effect, and (2) electron transit time (the time required to travel from cathode to anode).
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] Transit time effects are complicated, but one simple effect is the phase margin; another one is input conductance, also known as grid loading.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] At extremely high frequencies, electrons arriving at the grid may become out of phase with those departing towards the anode.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] This imbalance of charge causes the grid to exhibit a reactance that is much less than its low-frequency "open circuit" characteristic.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] Acorn- as well as Lighthouse tubes and Nuvistors attempt to minimize this effect by arranging cathode, grid(s) and anode as closely spaced together as possible.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] The original range included about half a dozen tubes, designed to work in the VHF range.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] The 954 and 956 types are sharp and remote cut-off pentodes, respectively, all with indirect 6.3 V, 150 mA heaters.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] Types 957, 958 and 959 are for portable equipment and have 1.25 V NiCd battery heaters.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] The 957 is a medium-μ signal triode, the 958 is a transmitting triode with dual, paralleled filaments for increased emission, and the 959 is a sharp cut-off pentode like the 954.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] The 957 and 959 draw 50 mA heater current, the 958 twice as much.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] In 1942, the 958A with tightened emission specifications was introduced after it turned out that 958s with excessively high emission kept working after the filament power was turned off, the filament still sufficiently heating on the anode current alone.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] After the introduction of the miniature 7-pin base, the 954, 955 and 956 were made available with this base as 9001, 9002 and 9003.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] Larger, higher-power types such as the 316A, 368A, 388A, and 703A triodes and the 713A and 717A pentodes were referred to as *Doorknob* tubes.
[src:inductor/acorn-tube] The introduction of the EF50 was the first serious competition for the acorn design, and replaced the acorns in many roles, especially post-war when millions of surplus EF50s were dumped on the market.
[src:inductor/additron-tube] The **Additron** was an electron tube designed by Dr.
[src:inductor/additron-tube] Josef Kates, circa 1950, to replace the several individual electron tubes and support components required to perform the function of a single bit digital full adder.
[src:inductor/additron-tube] The Additron neither went into production at the Canadian Rogers Vacuum Tube Company, where the prototypes were built, nor was it used in the UTEC machine.
[src:inductor/additron-tube] It did make a widely publicized appearance at the 1950 Canadian National Exhibition operating an electronic game of Tic-Tac-Toe, dubbed *Bertie the Brain*, to show the marvels of electronic computing.
[src:inductor/additron-tube] The tube was registered with the Radio Television Manufacturing Association on 20 March 1951 as type 6047.
[src:inductor/airfoil] An **airfoil** (American English) or **aerofoil** (British English) is a streamlined body that is capable of generating significantly more lift than drag.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Wings, sails and propeller blades are examples of airfoils.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Foils which work in a similar way submerged in water are called hydrofoils.
[src:inductor/airfoil] When oriented at a suitable angle, a solid body moving through a fluid deflects the passing fluid, resulting in a force on the airfoil in the direction opposite to the deflection.
[src:inductor/airfoil] This force is known as an aerodynamic force and can be resolved into two components: lift (perpendicular to the freestream velocity) and drag (parallel to the freestream velocity).
[src:inductor/airfoil] The lift on an airfoil is primarily the result of its angle of attack.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Most foil shapes require a positive angle of attack to generate lift, but cambered airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Airfoils have different shapes for different speeds: those for subsonic flight have a rounded leading edge, while those for supersonic flight tend to be slimmer.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The deflection of air by an airfoil generates a lower-pressure region above and behind itself.
[src:inductor/airfoil] This pressure difference is accompanied by a velocity difference, as explained by Bernoulli's principle, so the resulting flowfield about the airfoil has a higher average velocity on the upper surface than on the lower surface.
[src:inductor/airfoil] In some situations (e.g., inviscid potential flow) the lift force can be related directly to the average top/bottom velocity difference without computing the pressure by using the concept of circulation and the Kutta–Joukowski theorem.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The wings and stabilizers of fixed-wing aircraft, as well as helicopter rotor blades, are built with airfoil-shaped cross sections.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Airfoils are also found in propellers, fans, compressors and turbines.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Sails are also airfoils, and the underwater surfaces of sailboats, such as the centerboard, rudder, and keel, are similar in cross-section and operate on the same principles as airfoils.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Swimming and flying creatures and even many plants and sessile organisms employ airfoils/hydrofoils, common examples being bird wings, the bodies of fish, and the shape of sand dollars.
[src:inductor/airfoil] An airfoil-shaped wing can create downforce on an automobile or other motor vehicle, improving traction.
[src:inductor/airfoil] When the wind is obstructed by an object such as a flat plate, a building, or the deck of a bridge, the object will experience drag and also an aerodynamic force perpendicular to the wind.
[src:inductor/airfoil] This does not mean the object qualifies as an airfoil.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Airfoils are highly-efficient lifting shapes, able to generate more lift than similarly sized flat plates of the same area, and able to generate lift with significantly less drag.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Airfoils are used in the design of aircraft, propellers, rotor blades, wind turbines and other applications of aeronautical engineering.
[src:inductor/airfoil] A lift and drag curve obtained in wind tunnel testing is shown on the right.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The curve represents an airfoil with a positive camber so some lift is produced at zero angle of attack.
[src:inductor/airfoil] With increased angle of attack, lift increases in a roughly linear relation, called the *slope* of the lift curve.
[src:inductor/airfoil] At about 18 degrees this airfoil stalls, and lift falls off quickly beyond that.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The drop in lift can be explained by the action of the upper-surface boundary layer, which separates and greatly thickens over the upper surface at and past the stall angle.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The thickened boundary layer's displacement thickness changes the airfoil's effective shape, in particular it reduces its effective camber, which modifies the overall flow field so as to reduce the circulation and the lift.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The thicker boundary layer also causes a large increase in pressure drag, so that the overall drag increases sharply near and past the stall point.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Airfoil design is a major facet of aerodynamics.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Various airfoils serve different flight regimes.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Asymmetric airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack, while a symmetric airfoil may better suit frequent inverted flight as in an aerobatic airplane.
[src:inductor/airfoil] In the region of the ailerons and near a wingtip a symmetric airfoil can be used to increase the range of angles of attack to avoid spin–stall.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Thus a large range of angles can be used without boundary layer separation.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Subsonic airfoils have a round leading edge, which is naturally insensitive to the angle of attack.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The cross section is not strictly circular, however: the radius of curvature is increased before the wing achieves maximum thickness to minimize the chance of boundary layer separation.
[src:inductor/airfoil] This elongates the wing and moves the point of maximum thickness back from the leading edge.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Supersonic airfoils are much more angular in shape and can have a very sharp leading edge, which is very sensitive to angle of attack.
[src:inductor/airfoil] A supercritical airfoil has its maximum thickness close to the leading edge to have a lot of length to slowly shock the supersonic flow back to subsonic speeds.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Generally such transonic airfoils and also the supersonic airfoils have a low camber to reduce drag divergence.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Modern aircraft wings may have different airfoil sections along the wing span, each one optimized for the conditions in each section of the wing.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Movable high-lift devices, flaps and sometimes slats, are fitted to airfoils on almost every aircraft.
[src:inductor/airfoil] A trailing edge flap acts similarly to an aileron; however, it, as opposed to an aileron, can be retracted partially into the wing if not used.
[src:inductor/airfoil] For many wings, the boundary layer of the air flow close to the upper surface rapidly becomes turbulent past the maximum thickness point, which increases the skin friction drag.
[src:inductor/airfoil] A **laminar flow wing** moves the maximum thickness point well back along the chord from a typical 25% chord position from to 60% from the leading edge or more.
[src:inductor/airfoil] This maintains smooth laminar flow over a larger percentage of the wing and significantly reduces drag.
[src:inductor/airfoil] However, surface contamination will disrupt the boundary layer, making it turbulent.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Insects, for example, impacting and sticking onto the wing will cause the loss of wedge shaped regions of laminar flow across the wing's surface.
[src:inductor/airfoil] This is a particular problem for aircraft with high take off speeds, since many insects are found near the ground making it unlikely that laminar flow can be sustained into the flight.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Gliders have seen widespread uptake of laminar flow airfoils due to their low speeds and need for low drag aerodynamic structures.
[src:inductor/airfoil] NASA's research in the 1980s revealed the practicality and usefulness of laminar flow wing designs and opened the way for laminar-flow applications on modern practical aircraft surfaces, from subsonic general aviation aircraft to transonic large transport aircraft, to supersonic designs.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Schemes have been devised to define airfoils – an example is the NACA system.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Various airfoil generation systems are also used.
[src:inductor/airfoil] An example of a general purpose airfoil that finds wide application, and pre–dates the NACA system, is the Clark-Y.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Today, airfoils can be designed for specific functions by the use of computer programs.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Some important parameters to describe an airfoil's shape are its *camber* and its *thickness*.
[src:inductor/airfoil] For example, an airfoil of the NACA 4-digit series such as the NACA 2415 (to be read as 2 – 4 – 15) describes an airfoil with a camber of 0.02 chord located at 0.40 chord, with 0.15 chord of maximum thickness.
[src:inductor/airfoil] In two-dimensional flow around a uniform wing of infinite span, the slope of the lift curve is determined primarily by the *trailing edge angle*.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The slope is greatest if the angle is zero; and decreases as the angle increases.
[src:inductor/airfoil] For a wing of finite span, the aspect ratio of the wing also significantly influences the slope of the curve.
[src:inductor/airfoil] As aspect ratio decreases, the slope also decreases.
[src:inductor/airfoil] 2. on a cambered airfoil, the aerodynamic center lies exactly one quarter of the chord behind the leading edge, but the position of the center of pressure moves when the angle of attack changes.
[src:inductor/airfoil] 3. the slope of the *lift coefficient versus angle of attack* line is $2\pi \!$ units per radian.
[src:inductor/airfoil] is the section lift coefficient when the angle of attack is zero.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Thin airfoil theory assumes the air is an inviscid fluid so does not account for the stall of the airfoil, which usually occurs at an angle of attack between 10° and 15° for typical airfoils.
[src:inductor/airfoil] In the mid-late 2000s, however, a theory predicting the onset of leading-edge stall was proposed by Wallace J.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Morris's subsequent refinements contain the details on the current state of theoretical knowledge on the leading-edge stall phenomenon.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Morris's theory predicts the critical angle of attack for leading-edge stall onset as the condition at which a global separation zone is predicted in the solution for the inner flow.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Morris's theory demonstrates that a subsonic flow about a thin airfoil can be described in terms of an outer region, around most of the airfoil chord, and an inner region, around the nose, that asymptotically match each other.
[src:inductor/airfoil] As the flow in the outer region is dominated by classical thin airfoil theory, Morris's equations exhibit many components of thin airfoil theory.
[src:inductor/airfoil] In thin airfoil theory, the width of the (2D) airfoil is assumed negligible, and the airfoil itself replaced with a 1D blade along its camber line, oriented at the angle of attack α.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Let the position along the blade be x, ranging from 0 at the wing's front to c at the trailing edge; the camber of the airfoil, *dy*⁄*dx*, is assumed sufficiently small that one need not distinguish between x and position relative to the fuselage.
[src:inductor/airfoil] The flow across the airfoil generates a circulation around the blade, which can be modeled as a vortex sheet of position-varying strength γ(*x*).
[src:inductor/airfoil] The Kutta condition implies that γ(*c*)=0, but the strength is singular at the bladefront, with γ(*x*)∝1⁄√*x* for *x* ≈ 0.
[src:inductor/airfoil] From the Biot–Savart law, the vorticity γ(*x*) produces a flow field $w(x)={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{c}{\frac {\gamma (x')}{x-x'}}\,dx'{\text{,}}$ oriented normal to the airfoil at x.
[src:inductor/airfoil] Since the airfoil is an impermeable surface, the flow $w(x)$ must balance an inverse flow from V.
[src:inductor/airfoil] By the small-angle approximation, V is inclined at angle α-*dy*⁄*dx* relative to the blade at position x, and the normal component is correspondingly (α-*dy*⁄*dx*)*V*.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The germanium **alloy-junction transistor**, or **alloy transistor**, was an early type of bipolar junction transistor, developed at General Electric and RCA in 1951 as an improvement over the earlier grown-junction transistor.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The usual construction of an alloy-junction transistor is a germanium crystal forming the base, with emitter and collector alloy beads fused on opposite sides.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] Indium and antimony were commonly used to form the alloy junctions on a bar of N-type germanium.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The collector junction pellet would be about 50 mils (thousandths of an inch) in diameter, and the emitter pellet about 20 mils.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The base region would be on the order of 1 mil (0.001 inches, 25 μm) thick.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] There were several types of improved alloy-junction transistors developed over the years that they were manufactured.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] All types of alloy-junction transistors became obsolete in the early 1960s, with the introduction of the planar transistor which could be mass-produced easily while alloy-junction transistors had to be made individually.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The first germanium planar transistors had much worse characteristics than alloy-junction germanium transistors of the period, but they cost much less, and the characteristics of planar transistors improved very rapidly, quickly exceeding those of all earlier germanium transistors.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy transistor** (**MAT**) was developed by Philco as an improved type of alloy-junction transistor, it offered much higher speed.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] It is constructed of a semiconductor crystal forming the base, into which a pair of wells are etched (similar to Philco's earlier surface-barrier transistor) on opposite sides then fusing emitter and collector alloy beads into the wells.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The **micro-alloy diffused transistor** (**MADT**), or **micro-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philco as an improved type of micro-alloy transistor; it offered even higher speed.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] It is a type of diffused-base transistor.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] Before using electrochemical techniques and etching depression wells into the base semiconductor crystal material, a heated diffused phosphorus gaseous layer is created over the entire intrinsic semiconductor base crystal, creating a N-type graded base semiconductor material.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The emitter well is etched very shallow into this diffused base layer.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] For high-speed operation, the collector well is etched all the way through the diffused base layer and through most of the intrinsic base semiconductor region, forming an extremely thin base region.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] A doping-engineered electric field was created in the diffused base layer to reduce the charge carrier base transit time (similar to the drift-field transistor).
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The **post-alloy diffused transistor** (**PADT**), or **post-alloy diffused-base transistor**, was developed by Philips (but GE and RCA filed for patent and Jacques Pankove of RCA received patent for it) as an improvement to the germanium alloy-junction transistor, it offered even higher speed.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The Philco micro-alloy diffused transistor had a mechanical weakness that ultimately limited their speed; the thin diffused base layer would break if made too thin, but to get high speed it needed to be as thin as possible.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] Also it was very hard to control alloying on both sides of such a thin layer.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The post-alloy diffused transistor solved this problem by making the bulk semiconductor crystal the collector (instead of the base), which could be as thick as necessary for mechanical strength.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The diffused base layer was created on top of this.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] Then two alloy beads, one P-type and one N-type were fused on top of the diffused base layer.
[src:inductor/alloy-junction-transistor] The bead having the same type as the base dopant then became part of the base and the bead having the opposite type from the base dopant became the emitter.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:inductor/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:inductor/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:inductor/inductor] An **inductor**, also called a **coil**, **choke**, or **reactor**, is a passive two-terminal electrical component that stores energy in a magnetic field when an electric current flows through it.
[src:inductor/inductor] An inductor typically consists of an insulated wire wound into a coil.
[src:inductor/inductor] When the current flowing through the coil changes, the time-varying magnetic field induces an electromotive force (*emf*), or voltage, in the conductor, described by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:inductor/inductor] According to Lenz's law, the induced voltage has a polarity (direction) which opposes the change in current that created it.
[src:inductor/inductor] As a result, inductors oppose any changes in current through them.
[src:inductor/inductor] An inductor is characterized by its inductance, which is the ratio of the voltage to the rate of change of current.
[src:inductor/inductor] In the International System of Units (SI), the unit of inductance is the henry (H) named for 19th century American scientist Joseph Henry.
[src:inductor/inductor] In the measurement of magnetic circuits, it is equivalent to ⁠weber/ampere⁠.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors have values that typically range from 1 μH (10−6 H) to 20 H.
[src:inductor/inductor] Many inductors have a magnetic core made of iron or ferrite inside the coil, which serves to increase the magnetic field and thus the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] Along with capacitors and resistors, inductors are one of the three passive linear circuit elements that make up electronic circuits.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors are widely used in alternating current (AC) electronic equipment, particularly in radio equipment.
[src:inductor/inductor] They are used to block AC while allowing DC to pass; inductors designed for this purpose are called chokes.
[src:inductor/inductor] They are also used in electronic filters to separate signals of different frequencies, and in combination with capacitors to make tuned circuits, used to tune radio and TV receivers.
[src:inductor/inductor] The term inductor seems to come from Heinrich Daniel Ruhmkorff, who called the induction coil he invented in 1851 an inductorium.
[src:inductor/inductor] An electric current flowing through a conductor generates a magnetic field surrounding it.
[src:inductor/inductor] The magnetic flux linkage $\Phi _{\mathbf {B} }$ generated by a given current I depends on the geometric shape of the circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] The inductance of a circuit depends on the geometry of the current path as well as the magnetic permeability of nearby materials.
[src:inductor/inductor] An inductor is a component consisting of a wire or other conductor shaped to increase the magnetic flux through the circuit, usually in the shape of a coil or helix, with two terminals.
[src:inductor/inductor] Winding the wire into a coil increases the number of times the magnetic flux lines link the circuit, increasing the field and thus the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] The more turns, the higher the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] The inductance also depends on the shape of the coil, separation of the turns, and many other factors.
[src:inductor/inductor] By adding a "magnetic core" made of a ferromagnetic material like iron inside the coil, the magnetizing field from the coil will induce magnetization in the material, increasing the magnetic flux.
[src:inductor/inductor] The high permeability of a ferromagnetic core can increase the inductance of a coil by a factor of several thousand over what it would be without it.
[src:inductor/inductor] Any change in the current through an inductor creates a changing flux, inducing a voltage across the inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] if L is independent of time, current and magnetic flux linkage.
[src:inductor/inductor] Thus, inductance is also a measure of the amount of electromotive force (voltage) generated for a given rate of change of current.
[src:inductor/inductor] This is usually taken to be the constitutive relation (defining equation) of the inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] As with any antiderivative, a constant of integration is added to represent the initial current *I*(*t*0).
[src:inductor/inductor] The dual of the inductor is the capacitor, which stores energy in an electric field rather than a magnetic field.
[src:inductor/inductor] Its current–voltage relation replaces L with the capacitance C and has current and voltage swapped from these equations.
[src:inductor/inductor] The polarity (direction) of the induced voltage is given by Lenz's law, which states that the induced voltage will be such as to oppose the change in current.
[src:inductor/inductor] For example, if the current through an inductor is increasing, the induced potential difference will be positive at the current's entrance point and negative at the exit point, tending to oppose the additional current.
[src:inductor/inductor] The energy from the external circuit necessary to overcome this potential "hill" is being stored in the magnetic field of the inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] If the current is decreasing, the induced voltage will be negative at the current's entrance point and positive at the exit point, tending to maintain the current.
[src:inductor/inductor] In this case energy from the magnetic field is being returned to the circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] When there is a change in current through an inductor there is a change in the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:inductor/inductor] For example, if the current is increased, the magnetic field increases.
[src:inductor/inductor] This, however, does not come without a price.
[src:inductor/inductor] The magnetic field contains potential energy, and increasing the field strength requires more energy to be stored in the field.
[src:inductor/inductor] This energy comes from the electric current through the inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] The increase in the magnetic potential energy of the field is provided by a corresponding drop in the electric potential energy of the charges flowing through the windings.
[src:inductor/inductor] This appears as a voltage drop across the windings as long as the current increases.
[src:inductor/inductor] Once the current is no longer increased and is held constant, the energy in the magnetic field is constant and no additional energy must be supplied, so the voltage drop across the windings disappears.
[src:inductor/inductor] Similarly, if the current through the inductor decreases, the magnetic field strength decreases, and the energy in the magnetic field decreases.
[src:inductor/inductor] This energy is returned to the circuit in the form of an increase in the electrical potential energy of the moving charges, causing a voltage rise across the windings.
[src:inductor/inductor] The work done per unit charge on the charges passing through the inductor is $-{\mathcal {E}}$ .
[src:inductor/inductor] The negative sign indicates that the work is done *against* the emf, and is not done *by* the emf.
[src:inductor/inductor] The current I is the charge per unit time passing through the inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] In a ferromagnetic core inductor, when the magnetic field approaches the level at which the core saturates, the inductance will begin to change, it will be a function of the current $L(I)$ .
[src:inductor/inductor] For inductors with magnetic cores, the above equation is only valid for linear regions of the magnetic flux, at currents below the saturation level of the inductor, where the inductance is approximately constant.
[src:inductor/inductor] Where this is not the case, the integral form must be used with $L_{d}$ variable.
[src:inductor/inductor] The constitutive equation describes the behavior of an *ideal inductor* with inductance L , and without resistance, capacitance, or energy dissipation.
[src:inductor/inductor] In practice, inductors do not follow this theoretical model; *real inductors* have a measurable resistance due to the resistance of the wire and energy losses in the core, and parasitic capacitance between turns of the wire.
[src:inductor/inductor] A real inductor's capacitive reactance rises with frequency, and at a certain frequency, the inductor will behave as a resonant circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] Above this self-resonant frequency, the capacitive reactance is the dominant part of the inductor's impedance.
[src:inductor/inductor] At higher frequencies, resistive losses in the windings increase due to the skin effect and proximity effect.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors with ferromagnetic cores experience additional energy losses due to hysteresis and eddy currents in the core, which increase with frequency.
[src:inductor/inductor] At high currents, magnetic core inductors also show sudden departure from ideal behavior due to nonlinearity caused by magnetic saturation of the core.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors radiate electromagnetic energy into surrounding space and may absorb electromagnetic emissions from other circuits, resulting in potential electromagnetic interference.
[src:inductor/inductor] An early solid-state electrical switching and amplifying device called a saturable reactor exploits saturation of the core as a means of stopping the inductive transfer of current via the core.
[src:inductor/inductor] The winding resistance appears as a resistance in series with the inductor; it is referred to as DCR (DC resistance).
[src:inductor/inductor] This resistance dissipates some of the reactive energy.
[src:inductor/inductor] The quality factor (or *Q*) of an inductor is the ratio of its inductive reactance to its resistance at a given frequency, and is a measure of its efficiency.
[src:inductor/inductor] The higher the Q factor of the inductor, the closer it approaches the behavior of an ideal inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] High Q inductors are used with capacitors to make resonant circuits in radio transmitters and receivers.
[src:inductor/inductor] The higher the Q is, the narrower the bandwidth of the resonant circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] At low frequencies and within limits, increasing the number of turns *N* improves *Q* because *L* varies as *N*2 while *R* varies linearly with *N*.
[src:inductor/inductor] Similarly increasing the radius *r* of an inductor improves (or increases) *Q* because *L* varies with *r*2 while *R* varies linearly with *r*.
[src:inductor/inductor] So high *Q* air core inductors often have large diameters and many turns.
[src:inductor/inductor] Both of those examples assume the diameter of the wire stays the same, so both examples use proportionally more wire.
[src:inductor/inductor] If the total mass of wire is held constant, then there would be no advantage to increasing the number of turns or the radius of the turns because the wire would have to be proportionally thinner.
[src:inductor/inductor] Using a high permeability ferromagnetic core can greatly increase the inductance for the same amount of copper, so the core can also increase the Q.
[src:inductor/inductor] Cores however also introduce losses that increase with frequency.
[src:inductor/inductor] The core material is chosen for best results for the frequency band.
[src:inductor/inductor] High Q inductors must avoid saturation; one way is by using a (physically larger) air core inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] At VHF or higher frequencies an air core is likely to be used.
[src:inductor/inductor] A well designed air core inductor may have a Q of several hundred.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors are used extensively in analog circuits and signal processing.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors are used as the energy storage device in many switched-mode power supplies to produce DC current.
[src:inductor/inductor] The inductor supplies energy to the circuit to keep current flowing during the "off" switching periods and enables topographies where the output voltage is higher than the input voltage.
[src:inductor/inductor] A tuned circuit, consisting of an inductor connected to a capacitor, acts as a resonator for oscillating current.
[src:inductor/inductor] Tuned circuits are widely used in radio frequency equipment such as radio transmitters and receivers, as narrow bandpass filters to select a single frequency from a composite signal, and in electronic oscillators to generate sinusoidal signals.
[src:inductor/inductor] Two (or more) inductors in proximity that have coupled magnetic flux (mutual inductance) form a transformer, which is a fundamental component of every electric utility power grid.
[src:inductor/inductor] The efficiency of a transformer may decrease as the frequency increases due to eddy currents in the core material and skin effect on the windings.
[src:inductor/inductor] The size of the core can be decreased at higher frequencies.
[src:inductor/inductor] For this reason, aircraft use 400 hertz alternating current rather than the usual 50 or 60 hertz, allowing a great saving in weight from the use of smaller transformers.
[src:inductor/inductor] Transformers enable switched-mode power supplies that galvanically isolate the output from the input.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors are also employed in electrical transmission systems, where they are used to limit switching currents and fault currents.
[src:inductor/inductor] In this field, they are more commonly referred to as reactors.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors have parasitic effects which cause them to depart from ideal behavior.
[src:inductor/inductor] They create and suffer from electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:inductor/inductor] Their physical size prevents them from being integrated on semiconductor chips.
[src:inductor/inductor] So the use of inductors is declining in modern electronic devices, particularly compact portable devices.
[src:inductor/inductor] Real inductors are increasingly being replaced by active circuits such as the gyrator which can synthesize inductance using capacitors.
[src:inductor/inductor] cylinder, suppresses electronic noise in a computer power cord.
[src:inductor/inductor] An inductor usually consists of a coil of conducting material, typically insulated copper wire, wrapped around a core either of plastic (to create an air-core inductor) or of a ferromagnetic (or ferrimagnetic) material; the latter is called an "iron core" inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] The high permeability of the ferromagnetic core increases the magnetic field and confines it closely to the inductor, thereby increasing the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] Low frequency inductors are constructed like transformers, with cores of electrical steel laminated to prevent eddy currents.
[src:inductor/inductor] 'Soft' ferrites are widely used for cores above audio frequencies, since they do not cause the large energy losses at high frequencies that ordinary iron alloys do.
[src:inductor/inductor] Some inductors have an adjustable core, which enables changing of the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors used to block very high frequencies are sometimes made by stringing a ferrite bead on a wire.
[src:inductor/inductor] Small inductors can be etched directly onto a printed circuit board by laying out the trace in a spiral pattern.
[src:inductor/inductor] Some such planar inductors use a planar core.
[src:inductor/inductor] Small value inductors can also be built on integrated circuits using the same processes that are used to make interconnects.
[src:inductor/inductor] Aluminium interconnect is typically used, laid out in a spiral coil pattern.
[src:inductor/inductor] However, the small dimensions limit the inductance, and it is far more common to use a circuit called a *gyrator* that uses a capacitor and active components to behave similarly to an inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] Regardless of the design, because of the low inductances and low power dissipation on-die inductors allow, they are currently only commercially used for high frequency RF circuits.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors used in power regulation systems, lighting, and other systems that require low-noise operating conditions, are often partially or fully shielded.
[src:inductor/inductor] In telecommunication circuits employing induction coils and repeating transformers shielding of inductors in close proximity reduces circuit cross-talk.
[src:inductor/inductor] The term *air core coil* describes an inductor that does not use a magnetic core made of a ferromagnetic material.
[src:inductor/inductor] The term refers to coils wound on plastic, ceramic, or other nonmagnetic forms, as well as those that have only air inside the windings.
[src:inductor/inductor] Air core coils have lower inductance than ferromagnetic core coils, but are often used at high frequencies because they are free from energy losses called core losses that occur in ferromagnetic cores, which increase with frequency.
[src:inductor/inductor] A side effect that can occur in air core coils in which the winding is not rigidly supported on a form is 'microphony': mechanical vibration of the windings can cause variations in the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] At high frequencies, particularly radio frequencies (RF), inductors have higher resistance and other losses.
[src:inductor/inductor] In addition to causing power loss, in resonant circuits this can reduce the Q factor of the circuit, broadening the bandwidth.
[src:inductor/inductor] In RF inductors specialized construction techniques are used to minimize these losses.
[src:inductor/inductor] To reduce parasitic capacitance and proximity effect, high Q RF coils are constructed to avoid having many turns lying close together, parallel to one another.
[src:inductor/inductor] The windings of RF coils are often limited to a single layer, and the turns are spaced apart.
[src:inductor/inductor] To reduce resistance due to skin effect, in high-power inductors such as those used in transmitters the windings are sometimes made of a metal strip or tubing which has a larger surface area, and the surface is silver-plated.
[src:inductor/inductor] These are occasionally wound on a vertical insulating supports with dowels or slots, with the wire weaving in and out through the slots.
[src:inductor/inductor] Another construction technique with similar advantages is flat spiral coils.
[src:inductor/inductor] The form has an odd number of slots, so successive turns of the spiral lie on opposite sides of the form, increasing separation.
[src:inductor/inductor] Instead of a single solid conductor, litz wire consists of a number of smaller wire strands that carry the current.
[src:inductor/inductor] , the strands are insulated from each other, to prevent skin effect from forcing the current to the surface, and are twisted or braided together.
[src:inductor/inductor] The twist pattern ensures that each wire strand spends the same amount of its length on the outside of the wire bundle, so skin effect distributes the current equally between the strands, resulting in a larger cross-sectional conduction area than an equivalent single wire.
[src:inductor/inductor] Small inductors for low current and low power are made in molded cases resembling resistors.
[src:inductor/inductor] These may be either plain (phenolic) core or ferrite core.
[src:inductor/inductor] An ohmmeter readily distinguishes them from similar-sized resistors by showing the low resistance of the inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] Ferromagnetic-core or iron-core inductors use a magnetic core made of a ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic material such as iron or ferrite to increase the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] A magnetic core can increase the inductance of a coil by a factor of several thousand, by increasing the magnetic field due to its higher magnetic permeability.
[src:inductor/inductor] , the changing magnetic field can induce circulating loops of electric current in the conductive metal core.
[src:inductor/inductor] The amount of energy lost increases with the area inside the loop of current.
[src:inductor/inductor] The energy loss is proportional to the area of the hysteresis loop in the BH graph of the core material.
[src:inductor/inductor] have narrow hysteresis loops and so low hysteresis losses.
[src:inductor/inductor] Core loss is non-linear with respect to both frequency of magnetic fluctuation and magnetic flux density.
[src:inductor/inductor] Frequency of magnetic fluctuation is the frequency of AC current in the electric circuit; magnetic flux density corresponds to current in the electric circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] Magnetic fluctuation gives rise to hysteresis, and magnetic flux density causes eddy currents in the core.
[src:inductor/inductor] These nonlinearities are distinguished from the threshold nonlinearity of saturation.
[src:inductor/inductor] At low frequencies and over limited frequency spans (maybe a factor of 10), core loss may be treated as a linear function of frequency with minimal error.
[src:inductor/inductor] However, even in the audio range, nonlinear effects of magnetic core inductors are noticeable and of concern.
[src:inductor/inductor] , the inductance will fall and current will rise dramatically.
[src:inductor/inductor] This is a nonlinear threshold phenomenon and results in distortion of the signal.
[src:inductor/inductor] the current through iron core inductors must be limited below the saturation level.
[src:inductor/inductor] Some laminated cores have a narrow air gap in them for this purpose, and powdered iron cores have a distributed air gap.
[src:inductor/inductor] This allows higher levels of magnetic flux and thus higher currents through the inductor before it saturates.
[src:inductor/inductor] If the temperature of a ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic core rises to a specified level, the magnetic domains dissociate, and the material becomes paramagnetic, no longer able to support magnetic flux.
[src:inductor/inductor] The inductance falls and current rises dramatically, similarly to what happens during saturation.
[src:inductor/inductor] The effect is reversible: When the temperature falls below the Curie point, magnetic flux resulting from current in the electric circuit will realign the magnetic domains of the core and its magnetic flux will be restored.
[src:inductor/inductor] Low-frequency inductors are often made with laminated cores to prevent eddy currents, using construction similar to transformers.
[src:inductor/inductor] The core is made of stacks of thin steel sheets or laminations oriented parallel to the field, with an insulating coating on the surface.
[src:inductor/inductor] The insulation prevents eddy currents between the sheets, so any remaining currents must be within the cross sectional area of the individual laminations, reducing the area of the loop and thus reducing the energy losses greatly.
[src:inductor/inductor] The laminations are made of low-conductivity silicon steel to further reduce eddy current losses.
[src:inductor/inductor] For higher frequencies, inductors are made with cores of ferrite.
[src:inductor/inductor] Ferrite is a ceramic ferrimagnetic material that is nonconductive, so eddy currents cannot flow within it.
[src:inductor/inductor] The formulation of ferrite is xxFe2O4 where xx represents various metals.
[src:inductor/inductor] For inductor cores soft ferrites are used, which have low coercivity and thus low hysteresis losses.
[src:inductor/inductor] Another material is powdered iron cemented with a binder.
[src:inductor/inductor] Medium frequency equipment almost exclusively uses powdered iron cores, and inductors and transformers built for the lower shortwaves are made using either cemented powdered iron or ferrites.
[src:inductor/inductor] In an inductor wound on a straight rod-shaped core, the magnetic field lines emerging from one end of the core must pass through the air to re-enter the core at the other end.
[src:inductor/inductor] This reduces the field, because much of the magnetic field path is in air rather than the higher permeability core material and is a source of electromagnetic interference.
[src:inductor/inductor] A higher magnetic field and inductance can be achieved by forming the core in a closed magnetic circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] The magnetic field lines form closed loops within the core without leaving the core material.
[src:inductor/inductor] The shape often used is a toroidal or doughnut-shaped ferrite core.
[src:inductor/inductor] Because of their symmetry, toroidal cores allow a minimum of the magnetic flux to escape outside the core (called *leakage flux*), so they radiate less electromagnetic interference than other shapes.
[src:inductor/inductor] Toroidal core coils are manufactured of various materials, primarily ferrite, powdered iron and laminated cores.
[src:inductor/inductor] Probably the most common type of variable inductor today is one with a moveable ferrite magnetic core, which can be slid or screwed in or out of the coil.
[src:inductor/inductor] Moving the core farther into the coil increases the permeability, increasing the magnetic field and the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] Many inductors used in radio applications (usually less than 100 MHz) use adjustable cores in order to tune such inductors to their desired value, since manufacturing processes have certain tolerances (inaccuracy).
[src:inductor/inductor] Sometimes such cores for frequencies above 100 MHz are made from highly conductive non-magnetic material such as aluminium.
[src:inductor/inductor] They decrease the inductance because the magnetic field must bypass them.
[src:inductor/inductor] Air core inductors can use sliding contacts or multiple taps to increase or decrease the number of turns included in the circuit, to change the inductance.
[src:inductor/inductor] A type much used in the past but mostly obsolete today has a spring contact that can slide along the bare surface of the windings.
[src:inductor/inductor] The disadvantage of this type is that the contact usually short-circuits one or more turns.
[src:inductor/inductor] These turns act like a single-turn short-circuited transformer secondary winding; the large currents induced in them cause power losses.
[src:inductor/inductor] A type of continuously variable air core inductor is the *variometer*.
[src:inductor/inductor] This consists of two coils with the same number of turns connected in series, one inside the other.
[src:inductor/inductor] The inner coil is mounted on a shaft so its axis can be turned with respect to the outer coil.
[src:inductor/inductor] When the two coils' axes are collinear, with the magnetic fields pointing in the same direction, the fields add and the inductance is maximum.
[src:inductor/inductor] When the inner coil is turned so its axis is at an angle with the outer, the mutual inductance between them is smaller so the total inductance is less.
[src:inductor/inductor] When the inner coil is turned 180° so the coils are collinear with their magnetic fields opposing, the two fields cancel each other and the inductance is very small.
[src:inductor/inductor] This type has the advantage that it is continuously variable over a wide range.
[src:inductor/inductor] It is used in antenna tuners and matching circuits to match low frequency transmitters to their antennas.
[src:inductor/inductor] Another method to control the inductance without any moving parts requires an additional DC current bias winding which controls the permeability of an easily saturable core material.
[src:inductor/inductor] A choke is an inductor designed specifically for blocking high-frequency alternating current (AC) in an electrical circuit, while allowing DC or low-frequency signals to pass.
[src:inductor/inductor] Because the inductor restricts or "chokes" the changes in current, this type of inductor is called a choke.
[src:inductor/inductor] It usually consists of a coil of insulated wire wound on a magnetic core, although some consist of a donut-shaped "bead" of ferrite material strung on a wire.
[src:inductor/inductor] Like other inductors, chokes resist changes in current passing through them increasingly with frequency.
[src:inductor/inductor] The difference between chokes and other inductors is that chokes do not require the high Q factor construction techniques that are used to reduce the resistance in inductors used in tuned circuits.
[src:inductor/inductor] The effect of an inductor in a circuit is to oppose changes in current through it by developing a voltage across it proportional to the rate of change of the current.
[src:inductor/inductor] An ideal inductor would offer no resistance to a constant direct current; however, only superconducting inductors have truly zero electrical resistance.
[src:inductor/inductor] When there is a sinusoidal alternating current (AC) through an inductor, a sinusoidal voltage is induced.
[src:inductor/inductor] The amplitude of the voltage is proportional to the product of the amplitude ( $I_{P}$ ) of the current and the angular frequency ( $\omega$ ) of the current.
[src:inductor/inductor] In this situation, the phase of the current lags that of the voltage by ⁠π/2⁠ (90°).
[src:inductor/inductor] For sinusoids, as the voltage across the inductor goes to its maximum value, the current goes to zero, and as the voltage across the inductor goes to zero, the current through it goes to its maximum value.
[src:inductor/inductor] The ratio of the peak voltage to the peak current in an inductor energised from an AC source is called the reactance and is denoted XL.
[src:inductor/inductor] Reactance is measured in ohms but referred to as *impedance* rather than resistance; energy is stored in the magnetic field as current rises and discharged as current falls.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductive reactance is proportional to frequency.
[src:inductor/inductor] At low frequency the reactance falls; at DC, the inductor behaves as a short circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] As frequency increases the reactance increases and at a sufficiently high frequency the reactance approaches that of an open circuit.
[src:inductor/inductor] Inductors in a parallel configuration each have the same potential difference (voltage).
[src:inductor/inductor] The current through inductors in series stays the same, but the voltage across each inductor can be different.
[src:inductor/inductor] The sum of the potential differences (voltage) is equal to the total voltage.
[src:inductor/inductor] These simple relationships hold true only when there is no mutual coupling of magnetic fields between individual inductors.
[src:inductor/inductor] Mutual inductance occurs when the magnetic field of an inductor induces a magnetic field in an adjacent inductor.
[src:inductor/inductor] Mutual induction is the basis of transformer construction.
[src:inductor/inductor] where M as shown is the maximum possible mutual inductance between 2 inductors and L1 and L2 are the two inductors.
[src:inductor/inductor] as only a fraction of self flux is linked with the other.
[src:inductor/inductor] This fraction is called "coefficient of flux linkage" ( $\ K\$ ) or "coupling coefficient" (with $\ 0\leq K\leq 1\$ ).
